This PR also fixes an issue we've just experienced when merging two anchors into a node, see the following example:

``` yaml
item: &item
  key:
    inner_key: 'foo'

item_two: &item_two
  key_two:
    inenr_key_two: 'bar'

item_three:
  node:
    <<: *item
    key_three:
      inner_key_three: 'value'
    <<: *item_two   
```

In the current stable version of the parser you get the following result:

``` php
array(3) {
  ["item"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["key"]=>
    array(1) {
      ["inner_key"]=>
      string(3) "foo"
    }
  }
  ["item_two"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["key_two"]=>
    array(1) {
      ["inenr_key_two"]=>
      string(3) "bar"
    }
  }
  ["item_three"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["node"]=>
    array(1) {
      ["key_two"]=>
      array(1) {
        ["inenr_key_two"]=>
        string(3) "bar"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

As you can see the merge of the first `*item` and existing node `key_three` are lost and overwritten by `key_two`...

When I tested my example against this PR, I get the expected output:

``` php
array(3) {
  ["item"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["key"]=>
    array(1) {
      ["inner_key"]=>
      string(3) "foo"
    }
  }
  ["item_two"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["key_two"]=>
    array(1) {
      ["inenr_key_two"]=>
      string(3) "bar"
    }
  }
  ["item_three"]=>
  array(1) {
    ["node"]=>
    array(3) {
      ["key"]=>
      array(1) {
        ["inner_key"]=>
        string(3) "foo"
      }
      ["key_three"]=>
      array(1) {
        ["inner_key_three"]=>
        string(5) "value"
      }
      ["key_two"]=>
      array(1) {
        ["inenr_key_two"]=>
        string(3) "bar"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

> I also tested this in ruby with the built in yaml parser and it outputs the same result as this PR.

:+1: for getting this merged if the contributors are happy with it.

